It was himself, who three years ago criticized Bush's idea of sending new military reinforcements to Iraq, the country that is suffering from the civil war, and that criticized him as "an irresponsible and catastrophic decision."
The following months, however, showed that Bush's strategy, based on the recommendations of field captains, was the only possible and successful one, so that nothing about Iraq is spoken of today in the news.
Bush's reputation did not improve, but objectively left his successor a much more favorable initial situation than he might have expected.
In Afghanistan, Barack Obama hopes that the miracle will be repeated.
The camp captains again asked him to increase the military contingent, especially the commander-in-chief of the Afghan General Operation Stanley McCristal. He, despite the traditional subordinate relations, submitted to the indecisive gunmen in the White House a harsh criticism.
He asked for 40,000 men to be able to improve the situation.
The president wavered for three months, but nothing better happened to him, so at least he tricked the general over 10,000 soldiers.
He managed to get Europe to promise him another 5,000, although he himself previously had at least 10,000.
The most problematic of Obama’s whole strategy seems to be its goal, to start withdrawing troops from Afghanistan in 18 months and to finish this procedure in three years. Obama’s entire doctrine generated more questions than he offered.
Many doubt that the increase is the same as the procedure in Iraq.
Despite the fratricidal wars in recent years, Iraq's society is relatively well organized, its leaders respect the agreements.
The situation in Afghanistan is different: it is not possible to trust anyone and no agreement is being reached.
Under these conditions it is difficult to prepare Afghan security forces, if they are accustomed to changing their boss every day according to their needs.
Political institutions, although formally established, will remain only a people of Potemkin.After him will remain patriarchal tribal relations.
Balancing the interests of different ethnic groups is extraordinarily complicated due to confused relations, even more complicated by Pakistani and Iranian influences.
Not even establishing a state that is "capable of action", a minimum goal of the whole operation, seems very real.
The horizon of Obama's strategy is shocked by his volunteering.
Over the past eight years, the situation in Afghanistan has continued to deteriorate and is now about to explode.
Only a romantic soul, who knows nothing about reality, can believe that the military sent to war to "come home soon," will perform some miracle here.
From a political point of view, setting the date of withdrawal of troops is pure irresponsibility, as the Taliban will consider it as an indirect declaration of American defeat.
The latest NATO summit showed that Europeans are increasingly less willing to participate in military operations in Afghanistan.
European politicians do not know, nor do they want to explain to their voters what the security of Germany or Italy has to do with the war with Hindu Kush.
The other factor, capable of radically affecting the situation, is the development of developments in Iran.
If the situation continues to worsen and increased sanctions do not have any effect on the Iranians, the United States will have to make a difficult decision: try to solve the problem with military force or not.
It will be necessary to seek answers precisely when, according to Obama, America begins the triumphal withdrawal of troops from Afghanistan.
However, each solution will mean a dramatic reversal to the Afghan situation.
The only positive point for Barack Obama is the fact that there are three years left for the presidential elections and that is why there is still a lot of time to find another strategy, if this is a total failure.
