A Czech discovery: an effective substance up to the HIV virus 'inflicted'
The team of Czech and German scientists is testing new compounds that can moderate the spread of HIV in the body
The main advantage of this improved substance is the fact that it is also effective against drug-resistant viruses.
In some cases this is more important than the fact that the compound is not as effective in a common variant of the virus, as some medicines already accessible.
AIDS disease cannot be cured so far.
However, the lives of patients may be significantly prolonged by a mixture of medicines that prevent the replication of the HIV virus in the body.
However, its use has many side effects.
If the replication of the virus is not completely suppressed, so-called resistant viruses will be created; against them, drugs will no longer work.
The work of experts from three Institutes of the Academy of Sciences of the Czech Republic, VŠCHT Prague and Heidelberg University demonstrates the possibility of dominating the resistance of the virus.
They demonstrated that substances called metallocarbons have an effect on albumin, which is responsible for the spread of the HIV virus.
Metalocarbons are composed of boron, hydrogen, carbon and cobalt.
These compounds block the spread of the virus in a different way than all the medicines used today, and that is why they can solve the problem of resistance.
In their work scientists find new, ‘improved’ compounds, prepared knowing the molecular mechanism of their link to the virus albumin.
Metalocarbons have a single three-dimensional structure: two polyhedra cages composed of boron, hydrogen and carbon atoms are united by the metal atom, in this case by cobalt.
A Traitive and Resistant Virus
HIV protease is an albumin of the HIV virus, and it is essential for the vital cycle of the virus.
Without HIV protease, HIV virus fractionation would not occur and the virus would not create mature and infectious bodies.
