Management Revolution or End of Business Intelligence?
If nothing changes in the management of the large French companies, our struggle for the development of business intelligence will have been in vain...
More than ten years ago, the attitude of the management of large companies with regard to their employees recalls the position of companies with regard to consumers before the marketing revolution: it is a matter for employees to adhere to "values" determined from above as previously concerned to impose on consumers products thought by factory technicians.
By putting the customer at the center of the company, the marketing revolution has given its place to the strategies of conquering markets... although the authoritarian temptation to impose products that are unrelated to customer preference factors is repeated regularly.
Demobilization of employees can end up in deadly demoralization.
Suicides in France Telecom, PSA or Renault are only the tip of the iceberg of a much more general phenomenon that particularly affects executives.
This demobilization seriously compromises the development of all the intellectual functions of the company, especially R & D and even more business intelligence.
In fact, the BI (Business Intelligence) "requires that all parties involved (...) have proactive behaviour and a prospective vision"; this requires employees to make a commitment that is completely opposed to the recommendations of an authoritarian leadership.
For this reason, we call for a management revolution, which would consist of putting the employees at the heart of the company’s concerns as well as the customer.
Internal opinion surveys have a relative usefulness
Will internal opinion surveys, such as Orange's questionnaire among its employees, encourage management revolution in practice?
Unfortunately, I'm afraid not.
-In principle, because I could verify that, in the face of a new situation, and after many rounds, all companies end up doing essentially... what they always did! B989
- Secondly, because authoritarianism, one of the pathologies of power, grows proportionally to the importance of its own failures.
- Finally, because most managers have a simplistic view of human behavior.
As they come from large engineering schools, they interpret psychology mechanically.
They adopt, for intellectual comfort, the old conductist theory that the American "neurosciences" recently re-enacted, and that the Institutes of Studies and the media widely spread to their backs.
In this way, by suggesting that it is possible to manage the "commands" (sic) of the commitment of the executives, a recent investigation of Ipsos published in Le Figaro.fr reaffirms to the managers in a mechanical management position, which is not adapted to today's world.
Identify and measure mobilisation factors
On the contrary, the management revolution needed for the good functioning of modern companies means adopting a finalist view of human behavior.
It consists of integrating all reasoning or business management practice, a fundamental fact: for employees, commitment to the company is only possible if it appears clearly as a means to make reality part of their dreams, ambitions and projects.
Today, only studies from the Motifal Analysis adopt this conception of employee motivations.
Studies have shown that they judge their company based on a default dosage that allows them, through the image they have of the company, to evaluate what it offers them to achieve their own life projects.
Thanks to the identification and measurement of mobilisation factors, business managers can control, anticipate and anticipate their "social performance" and reposition the management of human resources "in place".
In this way, they create a favourable ground for the organized development of a strong and effective business intelligence.
