Last October, the Solera group purchased Autoonline, an internet platform for the sale of automobiles such as motorcycles or special vehicles.
The transaction amounted to EUR 59.5 million for 85% of the company's capital, which could be extended to the remaining 15% next year.
The objective of the acquisition was to offer more value-added services to its customers, with the possibility of accessing a huge international market.
This valuation and sales service is aimed exclusively at industry professionals, such as insurance companies, experts, rental companies, workshops, scraps and professional sellers who must register before they start operating.
This platform was established in 1996 in Germany and manages more than 650,000 operations across Europe, 500,000 of them in Germany.
Among its main markets are Spain, Greece, Poland and Turkey.
The website currently has more than 1,500 registered sellers and 4,000 experts.
3,000 daily ads are managed and some 100 new ads are included in the Spanish market each day.
Under Spanish law, a car whose rear number has been lowered cannot be recirculated, but can be used as a replacement for certain parts that are not damaged.
Historically-valued cars can get up even if they have been discharged after a tedious effort.
Four-step workshop budget
With the Auda-Taller tool, the Audatex company ensures that the user gets a budget in just four steps: identify the vehicle, look for the replacement, create the budget and generate the budget.
The ease of use is an essential condition for these systems, especially in order to convince older professionals that to a greater or lesser extent they are more reluctant to use new management techniques.
The database includes 1,034 vehicles, which are 666 tours, 109 totterrenos, 137 motorcycles, 78 vans and 44 trucks.
Of course, to use it requires a computer with Internet connection.
Once the model has been identified to be repaired by its background number, a real graphic image of the model in question appears and then the necessary replacement is selected.
The user can include variables such as labour price, charges or discounts, and then can print the budget to deliver to the customer.
AudaTaller is not an evaluation tool like AudaPlus, but rather a reference catalogue.
The main difference between both systems is that the workshop-oriented one does not include estimated working time.
The cost of using this tool for the workshop is EUR 350 per year, which the customer can finance.
Currently the company Audatex is working to make these images three-dimensional.
This is an innovation that mechanics see with very good eyes, as it will allow, for example, select a door and turn it around to see the inner face.
